<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18420613-1919">
               <interp inst="t18420613-1919" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18420613"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18420613-1919" type="date" value="18420613"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18420613-1919-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1919-18420613 t18420613-1919-offence-1 t18420613-1919-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1919. <persName id="def1-1919-18420613" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1919-18420613" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1919-18420613" type="age" value="63"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1919-18420613" type="surname" value="SEATHEARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1919-18420613" type="given" value="JEREMIAH THOMAS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JEREMIAH THOMAS SEATHEARD</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18420613-1919-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420613-1919-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420613-1919-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> for steal<lb></lb>ing, on the <rs id="t18420613-cd-183" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420613-1919-offence-1 t18420613-cd-183"></join>28th of April</rs>, 1 mangle, value 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; and 2 wooden rollers, value 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18420613-name-1062" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1062" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1062" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1062" type="given" value="NICHOLAS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1062" type="occupation" value="auctioneer"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420613-1919-offence-1 t18420613-name-1062"></join>Nicholas White</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHARNOCK</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1063" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1063" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1063" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1063" type="given" value="NICHOLAS"></interp>NICHOLAS WHITE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an auctioneer, living in Bridge-House-place, Newington-causeway. I let the prisoner the front and back parlours, on the left-hand side of a house in Three-Cup-alley, Shoreditch, about twenty months since—the two rooms on the right-hand side I reserved for myself, and in the front parlour on the right-hand I deposited a mangle—I did hot give the prisoner authority to take it out or sell it, or to go into that room—in consequence of information, I went into that room on Friday,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130187"></xptr>
               <p>the 13th of May, with the policeman—I found the prisoner, his wife, and another woman, in the same room where the mangle had been—they were apparently living there—I did not see the mangle—I pointed out the pri<lb></lb>soner to the policeman—the policeman said he was come to take him into custody for stealing the mangle—the prisoner said it was as much his as mine—I charged him with having removed it—he admitted it—he did not say where he had taken it—it was worth 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long was it since you had seen the prisoner before you went to take him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had not seen him since I let him the rooms—he paid me no rent—I did not apply to him for it—the house was in a dilapidated state—there were no other tenants in the house, of my letting, but I heard there were other persons there—I did not know who was in the house or out of it—I went into these rooms when I let them to the prisoner—I locked the mangle up in the front parlour—I cannot tell whether I went into the room that I had let to the prisoner when I went with the policeman—I went into the room where the mangle was in, directly, because the prisoner was to be secured—there are eight small rooms in the house—to my knowledge people have not gone in and out, paying no rent, but lodging as they had a mind—it is <hi rend="italic">my</hi> house—the mangle had been in the house two or three months before the prisoner went there—it had been in the next house; and having let the next house, I caused it to be removed into this room—the other house was in a dilapidated condition—I had let it, and not applied for the rent—the house in' which the prisoner lived was left me by will, by Mr. Hutton—the glass was all out before the prisoner came into it, and I put the glass all in—after the prisoner was in custody I got some glass from a shop—the prisoner's wife told me there was some glass that she had left there for 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I have not received any communication about glass from anybody since the prisoner has been there—I never said anything to anybody about not wishing to hurt the prisoner—the solicitor said, "I suppose you have no vindictive feelings?"—I said, "No, but I must put an end to stealing property in this way"—I have distained on the prisoner's wife lately, after first offering her goods if she would leave the place—there was a weekly rent to have been paid by the prisoner—it was not an understanding with the prisoner that I should not be paid any rent because the house was di<lb></lb>lapidated—very recently there was a quarrel with the prisoner's wife and a bad character, and they broke sixteen squares of glass—I believe the prisoner is a cutter-up of beef and ham at fairs—the rent was 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a week—I did not make a memorandum of it in a book—after he was in custody I told his wife she appeared not to be able to pay so much as the rent of two rooms; if she chose to go into a back room up stairs, she might—I have seen the mangle at Dawson's—I know it from a crack in the iron-work of the box, and from its general appearance.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHARNOCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you any doubt about its being yours? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not the slightest.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1064" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1064" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1064" type="surname" value="WILLIAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1064" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>JANE WILLIAMS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Edward Williams, and have lived in the same house where the prisoner did, in Three-Cup-alley, about nine months; the mangle was in the room on the left-band side—on the 28th of April, Mr. Dawson's men came with a cart—the prisoner was at the door, and Mr. Dawson's men took away the mangle—I did not hear any one give directions—I saw it put into the cart—I followed the cart to Mr. Dawson's house, in Old-street Road—when I got there I told the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130188"></xptr>
               <p>men it was not the prisoner's property, but it was Mr. White's—the mangle was then taken out of the cart, and taken into Mr. Dawson's—I after. wards saw it at Worship-street—I am sure it is the same mangle that was taken out of the house where I live, and the one taken to Dawson's and the one that Mr. White identified—it had been mended on the lid, and I knew it by some flat-headed nails driven in on the lid—I have no doubt it is the same I had seen removed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Yon were not on terms of intimacy with the pri<lb></lb>soner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was not—I lived at the top part of the house—I had never been in the rooms below—I never saw the mangle till I saw it taken out in the cart—I was at the top window, and looked down on the top of it—I saw the nails in it at Mr. Dawson's door—there was a large patch of black in the middle of the mangle—I did not pay any rent at that time—I have been living there nine months—I have paid rent to Mr. White since the 28th of April—I had only one room, and paid 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a week.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1065" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1065" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1065" type="surname" value="HORROD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1065" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH HORROD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a widow, living in Three-Cup-alley. I know there was a mangle on those premises—I do not know myself whose</p>
               <p>it was—I went there with the intention of purchasing it—I have since seen it at the police-office, and it is the one I saw on those premises.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Had you ever seen it before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, about a year and nine months ago—I did not buy it, because it was too dear——there was no crack in the iron-work—there was something the matter with the spindle, and the handle would not keep on—I did not offer 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and my own mangle for it—I have paid about a quarter of a year's rent—I took the place of Mrs. Fossett, not of the prosecutor.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1066" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1066" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1066" type="surname" value="DAWSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1066" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN DAWSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a furniture-broker, and live in Old-street-road. The prisoner called on my wife, and said he had got a mangle to sell, I sent two of my men for it, but I went to the premises first, and treated with the prisoner for the purchase of it—I was to give him 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for it—he asked 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or 7<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—the mangle came to my shop, and I paid for it—there was a mangle claimed by Mr. White, and he removed one—but I mean to swear he has removed a wrong mangle.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Was the one removed by Mr. White the one you got from the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was not, it was one I purchased of a man named Webb, who is here—the one I bought of the prisoner has the name of Moore croft on it, and the one they swore to was one of Baker's make—the mangle identified by Mr. White has one of the ears in two pieces—I was not present when the prosecutor identified the mangle, I was in bed—I did not object to their coming on my premises.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I suppose you have lost the best mangle? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It is, a great deal.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1067" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1067" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1067" type="surname" value="DUBOIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1067" type="given" value="HENRY WILLIAM"></interp>HENRY WILLIAM DUBOIS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable N</hi> 14.) I took the prisoner, and told him what he was charged with—I found this mangle in Daw<lb></lb>sou's cellar, and took it to the station—I said to the prisoner, "Is this the mangle?"—he said, "I believe it is." <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1068" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1068" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1068" type="surname" value="WEBB"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1068" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL WEBB</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a launderer, living in Ebury-farm-row—I have seen the mangle which is identified by the prosecutor—I sold it to Mr. Dawson, about six or seven weeks ago—I know it by two particular marks on the top—one is some nails which I had put in inside, where the panel slips in, and one of the ears is in two pieces, when it is off—I had these three nails put into the top, and there is a very black patch</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130189"></xptr>
               <p>on it that I scraped with a knife, and put putty and oil in, to stop the worm-holes, and the pencil-marks on the crosspieces, and where the ba<lb></lb>lance is put in, one of the pieces is shaken off.</p>
               <p>MR. <hi rend="smallCaps">CHARNOCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long have you been a landerer? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> The last eight years—I never knew the prisoner before I saw him at Wor<lb></lb>ship-street—this mangle came from Tatters ell's, at Hyde-park-corner—I bought it in the yard about a fortnight before I sold it to Dawson, for 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>, 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—a man named Loosely was present—I hired a cart of Ha<lb></lb>mar, a green-grocer—I gave him 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and the man half-a-crown, for helping me, and telling me it was to be sold—it was removed at four o'clock in the afternoon—there was no balance in it then—I sold it to Davson for 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I never bought and sold but two before—I never saw Dawson till I had the mangle to sell—I put a ticket in the window, "Baker's patent mangle for sale"—I had a great many applications, but could not get the price—Dawson came to me afterwards, and asked me if I should know it again, I said, "Yes, from a hundred"—I have been with Dawson several times—I came here with him—we have had very little together—on Thursday I brought my own dinner—on Friday we had a little repast, which Dawson paid for, and on Saturday—there were some nails in the mangle I sold—one was a tin tack—the black patch is on the crosspiece which the panel goes in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was it Mr. Dawson came to you about the mangle for the prisoner's friends? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Mr. Dawson—I bought it to sell again.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1069" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1069" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1069" type="surname" value="LOOSRLBY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1069" type="given" value="JOIIPH"></interp>JOIIPH LOOSRLBY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a carpenter, living in Queen-street, Pimlico—I was present when Webb bought a mangle—I marked it with my pencil on the cross pieces—one of the ears was in two pieces—I knew the mangle for four or five years at Mr. Tatters all's, at Hyde Park-corner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHAENOCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long have you known Webb? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Between four and five years—the marks were put on when I took the mangle to pieces, that I might put it up again.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1070" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1070" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1070" type="surname" value="EDWARDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1070" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS EDWARDS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a carman, living in Queen-street, Hoxton-market—I took this mangle from Mr. Webb to Dawson's—I know it by taking it from Mr. Webb to Mr. Dawson's—I put it up in the cellar, and there it remained, till Mr. White came and took it away—it had an oak bed—Mr. Dawson applied to me to come here—he sent me to Webb's for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHARNOCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How many mangles has Mr. Dawson? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Twenty or thirty—there is a great similarity between mangles—these are all put in the lower part of Mr. Dawson's premises for safe custody—I am the man that fetched a mangle from Three Cups-alley, on or about the 28th of April—I was not told that it was not the property of the man that sold it, to my recollection—it is often the case, where I fetch mangles and goods from, there is wrangling and jangling amongst the people—there are often disputes about the property ray master purchases—it makes no impression on me—I was not told it was stolen, and would be claimed by the owners—Mr. White's name was not mentioned—I fetched it about seven o'clock in the morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1071" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1071" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1071" type="surname" value="BURLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1071" type="given" value="HARRIET"></interp>HARRIET BURLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of a plasterer, living in Cock-lane, Church-lane, Shore ditch. I know the house in Three Cups-alley—I have been several times in the room of that house, where the mangle was, and used it—the one now produced is not it—I know it because one of our</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130190"></xptr>
               <p>little children put the candle on the end of the mangle, it fell down, and burnt a part as big as a sixpence.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHARNOCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When were you applied to come up? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> When the prisoner was taken up—I have known his wife twenty-two years, and she said to me, "Dear me, father is taken up for selling a mangle, and they have brought the wrong mangle"—I was sitting with his wife when he was taken, and they took me—I had two hours imprisonment—I used to have the mangle to mangle my things, and pay so much a dozen to Mrs. Seat herd—I remember no other mangle there but this—I had not been at the premises before the prisoner came—I am sure there was only one mangle. <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHARNOCK</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1072" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1072" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1072" type="surname" value="HILLS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1072" type="given" value="PETER"></interp>PETER HILLS</persName>
                  </hi>. I know the mangle that was on Mr. White's premise, in Three Cups-alley—I had known it nine or ten years—I hare pot it up ten or twelve times—it belonged originally to Mr. York Haltom, who is deceased—I went to Dawson's and saw it there, and identified it among many others—I have no doubt of it—I know it, because I repaired those places in it</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> When did you put it together last? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About two years ago—I have not put up many mangles since that—I was fore<lb></lb>man to Mr. York Halton—I have put it up in Three Cups-alley, in Kent-street, and Thames-street, City—it had been much used, but was standing by for years—the bed of it was oak—a person who works for Mr. White, asked me if I should know it—I said, yes—I met him and the policeman and went and identified it—when it was put up the last time, it was for Mr. Halton.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1073" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1073" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1073" type="surname" value="TOSSETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1073" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN TOSSETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I was present on the 28th of April, at seven o'clock in the morning, when the cart was at the door—there were other peoun there—I said to the men who were removing the mangle, that they were removing the mangle belonging to Mr. White of Newington-causeway—I followed the cart to Mr. Dawson's, and told them the same as I did at the house, that they were taking away stolen property.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Do you live in Three Cups-alley? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I pay <hi rend="italic">no</hi> rent—I have been there two years, and have paid no rent during that time—I was at my own door when I spoke to the men—I cannot tell whether they gave any answer to me—they paid no attention to what I said.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">

